div.div: 2005 notes: Unit not yet studied, but is a priority for comparison with 10380. Bone tools (metapodial points) are F1-5. F6 is a bone fish hook. F7-8 are bone points. Season 2006: A big midden out of the 4040. 2006 notes from actual analysis: A large midden unit. The usual assortment of weathering is generally mild to moderate, levels of digestion are low, and levels of burning are low (and almost all low-temperature). Pieces range in size from small up to extremely large. The large ones are both big chunks from cattle-sized animals and complete or nearly so ones from sheep-size animals. Lots of long bone shaft splinters, plenty of ribs <03-size but also 05, 07 present; a small part of them have marks; burning especially in low temperature; three pieces have pathological change like exostosis and osteomyelitis/infection in collum costae and below head of 05 size rib; three pieces have carnivore gnawing marks; there are filleting, dismembering and consumption marks, a reasonable number of vertebrae. Among the diagnostics, we have mostly sheep/goat, a reasonable quantity of cattle, some equid and fox, and a wolf tooth. Several pieces of both red deer and pig. Caprines are represented by the full range of ages and all body parts. Interesting pattern with astragali in that majority are sheep, and only 2 goats, which are the larger specimens. Also, of 18, 16 are right hand sides. A couple of complete metacarpals allow full measurements. Cranial remains are overwhelmingly 003 size (and diagnostics are sheep/goat), although cattle-sized animals are present in small numbers. Some of the caprine cranial remains are big pieces of very delicate bones, indicating minimal postdepositional disturbance of the unit. There is an anterior mandible of an immature pig (at symphysis, contains unerupted incisors) and posterior mandible of an equid.
